# Rust Ownership & Borrowing

The borrow checker is your ally. If you are fighting it, the design is wrong — not the compiler.

## Core rules

- Prefer borrowing (`&T`, `&mut T`) over owning (`T`) in function parameters unless the function needs to consume or store the value
- Accept `&str` instead of `&String`, `&[T]` instead of `&Vec<T>`, `&Path` instead of `&PathBuf` — these are strictly more general
- Never clone to satisfy the borrow checker without first asking: "can I restructure to avoid this?"
- Never use `Rc<RefCell<T>>` as a reflex — reach for it only after confirming a tree/graph ownership structure genuinely requires shared mutability

## Lifetimes

- Let the compiler elide lifetimes wherever possible — do not annotate what the elision rules already cover
- When lifetime annotations are required, name them meaningfully when there are multiple (`'input`, `'buf`) not just `'a`, `'b`
- Avoid `'static` bounds on trait objects unless the value truly must live forever (e.g. spawned threads); prefer bounded lifetimes
- `'static` string literals are fine; `Box<dyn Trait + 'static>` in an API is a design smell unless you are crossing thread boundaries

## Cloning & copying

- Derive `Copy` for small, trivially-copyable types (plain structs of primitives)
- Derive `Clone` for types that are cheap to duplicate logically but not bitwise
- When passing large structs, pass references — not clones
- `Arc::clone(&x)` is explicit and preferred over `x.clone()` for shared ownership to make it visible at the call site

## Interior mutability

- Use `Cell<T>` for `Copy` types; `RefCell<T>` for non-`Copy` types with single-threaded interior mutability
- Use `Mutex<T>` / `RwLock<T>` for multi-threaded interior mutability
- Document every `RefCell` / `Mutex` with a comment explaining the invariant that prevents panics/deadlocks

## Common anti-patterns

```rust
// BAD — unnecessary clone
fn print_name(name: &String) { println!("{name}"); }
// GOOD
fn print_name(name: &str) { println!("{name}"); }

// BAD — clone to dodge the borrow checker
let x = some_map.get(&key).unwrap().clone();
drop(some_map); // unlock conceptually
// GOOD — restructure the borrow scope or use entry API
```
